The sea is ours: landlocked Bolivia hopes the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
The sailors are constantly patrolling the rigged naval headquarters at La Paz.
The flag is a blue flag that flies over public buildings.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are adorned with the motto: "The sea is ours by right".
It's our duty to get it back.
Across Bolivia, which has no access to the ocean, the memory of the lost outlet handed to Chile after a bloody conflict in the 19th century is still alive  as is the call to sail the Pacific again.
In fact, that hope is now the strongest it has been in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the international court on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
"Strength is in Bolivia, there is a sense of cheerfulness and unity everywhere, as the country looks forward to a positive outcome", said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadala.
Many Bolivians will watch the ruling of the International Court of Justice on big screens across the country, hoping that the Hague tribunal will support Bolivia's claim and that after decades of negotiations Chile will be obliged to give Bolivia sovereign access to the ocean.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic local president, who is set to head into a contentious re-election battle next year, also placed a huge stake in the court's ruling on Monday.
"We are very close to regaining access to the Pacific Ocean", Morales promised last August.
But some analysts believe that the chances of the court ruling in favor of Bolivia are very slim, and even if it did, it would not change things in reality.
The UN body in the Netherlands has no authority to take over Chilean territory and has decided not to determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the International Court's ruling comes only six months after the last arguments were heard shows that the case is "not complicated", answers Paz Zarate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And instead of contributing to Bolivia's cause, the last four years may actually have hurt it.
"The problem of access to the ocean was inflated by the current Bolivian government", Zarate says.
Then he implied that Morales' bellicose rhetoric had wiped out what little goodwill Chile had left.
Bolivia and Chile will at some point resume negotiations, but it will be extremely difficult after what happened to have a normal dialogue.
The two countries have not maintained diplomatic missions in each other's country since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltze, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was being made unusually quickly.
He said that on Monday Bolivia will have "an incredible opportunity to open a new era in its relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of disagreement by achieving mutual benefits".
Calzada also rejected the idea that Morales  who continues to be one of Latin America's most popular presidents  used the issue of access to the ocean as a political grid.
'Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,' he added.
Judgment is an opportunity to see that we have to overcome our past problems.
