John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another outstanding performance in test scores, only reinforced by individual and collective achievements in sport, the arts, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30 000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Independent Schools Association (SCIS), strive to offer the best possible standard to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for their further education, their chosen careers and their place in a global world.
As an education sector that can design and implement a personalised curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said this: "If you talk to someone in a language they understand, your words reach them.
But if you speak his own language, you touch his heart.
It's a powerful reminder that we can't rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and trust with the people of other countries.
We see from this year's test results that languages are the top performers for independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students achieved A's in Chinese, with 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students achieving the same score.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland see foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Currently, languages as a subject of free choice for students are given the same treatment as natural and mathematical disciplines (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) both in the curricula of independent schools and beyond.
A 2014 study by the UK Employment and Skills Commission showed that 17% of employers cited insufficient language skills as a reason for their difficulty in recruiting.
Therefore, the knowledge of foreign languages is increasingly becoming a must to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more jobs require foreign language proficiency, making these skills essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you master a foreign language, you will have a real advantage in the future, having mastered such a skill that will last a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person one step ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to conduct a language, with French being the only language whose proficiency reached double-digit percentages at 15%.
That's why investing in language learning today is important for children now.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding good jobs.
In Scotland, each school will be different in the languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important for the UK in the future by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers being experts in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are firmly committed to providing an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, whatever the future holds.
At the moment, there is no denying that in a global business environment, languages continue to play an incredibly important role for the future of any country, which requires that they be taken into account in the education system.
And indeed, modern languages should really be considered as international communication skills.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellence, to young people in Scotland.
It's the right thing to do.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Independent Schools Association.
