North Korea says there's no way they can disarm unilaterally without trust.
North Korea's foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that continued sanctions were deepening mistrust of the United States and there was no way the country would unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
At the annual general assembly of the world organization, Ri Yong-ho said that "significant goodwill measures" have been taken over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, destroying the nuclear test site, and pledging to not spread nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States", he said.
Without trust in the United States, we will not have confidence in our own national security and under no circumstances can we disarm first unilaterally.
While Ri expressed North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "staged" approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking steps, his statement seemed significant because he did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work for the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula and Trump gave assurances for North Korea's security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
The US insists on "first eliminating nuclear weapons" and increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and even objecting to the "declaration of the end of the war", Ri said.
The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a meaningless dream for those who don't know us.
The problem, however, is that the continuing sanctions are deepening our mistrust".
Ri did not say whether a second meeting between Kim and Trump was planned, as the US leader stressed at the UN earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister focused on the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: "If the side on the nuclear disarmament issue were South Korea, not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a standstill.
However, the tone of Ri's speech was significantly different from the previous year when he told the UN General Assembly that the targeting of North Korean missiles at the US mainland was inevitable after the evil President Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
At the UN this year, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea with "total destruction", praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much work to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea eliminates its nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump stressed that there was no deadline for this, saying, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years, or five months".
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
