Harvard students on a course to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is getting all students to sleep more in an attempt to combat the growing culture of caffeinated all-nighter learning.
A professor found that students at the world's number one university often do not even think about the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Keisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after he spoke about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
Finally, a girl came up to me and said, "Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?"
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barrera, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
One section shows a dorm room where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books to explain the effects of caffeine and light, how poor sleep affects athletic performance, and the importance of a good bedtime routine.
In another section, participants discuss how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
We know that this will not immediately change the behaviour of the students.
But we believe they have a right to know  just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke, added Prof. Keisler.
The culture of pride in studying all night is still there, he says, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Providing enough quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" for students to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he says - even to avoid becoming fat, since sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, which makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student in California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Keisler prepare the course by taking one of his classes during his first year at Harvard.
He says the course was an eye opener and inspired him to spread it throughout campus.
It is hoped that the next step is for all graduate students to be asked to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competing institution.
Professor Keisler recommends that students consider setting bedtime and wake-up alarms and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt circadian rhythms and lead to sleep problems.
