But it's 6 a.m. on a Sunday, and there's no way to plan things so that here the event is on a Sunday and there it's on a Monday.
We're working on it.
Believe me, when the program was changed, we got a lot of messages, and not everyone was friendly.
We tried to fix it because we thought it was a technical problem.
But it wasn't. It was government.
I can promise you that next time it won't happen.
We're sticking with five games instead of six as usual, and we tried to give the fans more room, but we went too far.
This is an unpleasant situation.
Tom Daley felt inferior because of his sexuality.
Olympic water skier Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to everyone else because of his sexuality, but that's what motivated him to succeed.
The 24-year-old athlete claims that until he started high school, he didn't realize that "not everyone is like me".
In an interview for the first edition of Desert Island Discs on Radio 4, hosted by Lauren Laverne, he spoke about gay rights to give "hope" to others.
He also said that when he became a parent, he became less interested in winning the Olympics.
The longtime host of the show, Kirsty Young, has been hospitalized for several months.
On his first Laverne Daley show, he said he felt "less than everybody else" growing up because it wasn't socially acceptable to like both girls and boys.
He said, "To this day, the feeling of inferiority and being different from others are actually the things that give me the energy and strength to succeed".
He wanted to prove he was "something", he said, so he wouldn't disappoint anyone when he finally learned about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medallist has become an active LGBT campaigner and used his participation in this year's British Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalise homosexuality.
He said he did it because he was happy to be able to live openly without consequences and wanted to inspire hope in others.
The three-time world champion said that when he fell in love with a man -- American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 -- it "surprised" him.
Daly married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years his senior, last year, but claims the age difference was never an issue.
"When you go through so much when you're so young" He competed in his first Olympics at 14 and his father died of cancer three years later, he said, "It's hard to find someone your age who has had similar ups and downs".
The two became parents in June and have a son named Robert Ray Black-Daily, and Daley himself says his whole worldview has changed.
"If you had asked me last year, I would have told you that I was only interested in winning a gold medal", he said.
You know, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.
His son was named after his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at age 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daly said his father couldn't accept that he was going to die and one of the last things he asked was if they had tickets for the 2012 London Olympics because he wanted to be in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him you weren't going to be there for me, Dad, or in the front row", he said.
"I held his hand until he stopped breathing, and at that moment, when I realized he was dead, I finally admitted he wasn't invulnerable", he said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
"I just knew that I had dreamed of it all my life, jumping at the Olympics in front of the home crowd.
It also inspired his choice of his first song   Proud  by Heather Small  which accompanied him during his preparation for the Olympics and still makes him cringe.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 on Sundays at 11:15am, British Summer Time.
Missed form Mickelson remains on the bench for the Ryder Cup on Saturday.
American Phil Mickelson will set a record on Sunday when he plays his 47th Ryder Cup match, but he'll have to get back to his old form if he doesn't want his record to be tied to failure.
Mickelson, who is competing in the two-year-old event for a record 12th time, was left on the bench by captain Jim Furyk for the Fourball and FourSum matches on Saturday.
Instead of being a mainstay on the U.S. team again, the five-time major championship winner spent his days as a fan and practicing his long-range blows in the hope of correcting his weaknesses.
The 48-year-old, who even at the peak of his career was never among the most straightforward players, is not in the best shape for the difficult course of Le Golf National, where the long, uneven course usually punishes any wrong shot.
And if the court itself isn't disturbing enough, in Game 9 on Sunday, Mickelson will face defending British Open champion Francesco Molinari, who is teaming up with rookie Tommy Fleetwood and looking to win all four of his matches this week.
If the Americans, who are down by four points with 12 games left in the singles, get off to a strong start, it could be the decisive match for Mickelson.
Furyk expressed confidence in his teammate, though he could hardly have said anything much different.
"He fully understood his role today, patted me on the back, hugged me and said he'd be ready tomorrow", Furik said.
He's confident in himself.
He's a Hall of Famer and he gave as much last week as he did this week.
I probably didn't imagine him playing in two games.
I expected him to play more, but it just happened, and we believe we made the right decision.
He wants to be on the golf course and play like everybody else.
Mickelson will beat Nick Faldo's record for most Ryder Cup games played on Sunday.
This could end his Ryder Cup career, which has never come close to his impressive individual achievements.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven draws, but Furyk said his presence brings other benefits to the team that are not measured in numbers.
"He's funny, sarcastic, witty, likes to joke with people and is a great guy for any team", he explained.
I think the younger players were having fun with him, especially this week.
He gives a lot more than just playing.
Thomas Bjorn, the captain of Europe, is well aware that the great lead may soon be melted away.
Team Europe captain Thomas Bjorn knows from personal experience that the big lead accumulated before the singles matches of the last day of the Ryder Cup can easily be erased.
The Dane made his debut in Valderrama in 1997 when the team captained by Seve Ballesteros led by five points over the Americans, but just on the final right he was almost caught and barely managed to hold on to win by 141⁄2-131⁄2.
"You keep reminding yourself that we had a big lead at Valderrama; we had a big lead at Brooklyn where we lost, and we won at Valderrama, but very hard", Björn said after the 2018 European Team won by 53 sessions on Friday and yesterday, giving him a 106 lead at Le Golf National.
So history must show me and everyone on this team that it's not over.
Be ready for the attack tomorrow.
Go out there and do what you gotta do.
Nothing's over until you see the final scoreboard.
We have a goal and that is to try to win this trophy and that's what we need to stay focused on.
I kept saying that I was only thinking about the 12 players on our team, but we are also aware of our rivals, who are some of the greatest players in the world.
Satisfied with the players' performance on a difficult golf course, Bjorn added: "I would never rush the celebrations.
It'll be different tomorrow.
Tomorrow, the focus will be on individual performances, and this is different.
It's great to be out there with a partner when everything's going well, but when you're out there alone, that's when you put your full capacity as a golfer to the test.
That's the message that we need to get to the players: You have to give your best tomorrow.
Now you can turn your back on your partner, as he too must give himself up to the end.
Unlike Bjorn, the opposing team's captain, Jim Furyk, will want his players to perform better individually than as partners, with the only exceptions being Jordan Speight and Justin Thomas, who took three of four possible points.
Furyk himself was on both sides of these big reverses on the last day -- he was part of the Brooklyn triumph -- and then he was on the losing side when the Europeans performed the Miracle of Medina.
"I remember every damn word", he said in response to a question about how Ben Crenshaw, the 1999 captain, led his players on the final day.
We have 12 big games tomorrow, but you'd better make the same good start you saw at Brooklyn and Medina.
When the advantage shifts from one direction to the other, these middlegames are played under enormous tension.
So we've put our guys together and we've put our guys where we want them to be, so we can try to do the impossible tomorrow.
Thomas is tasked with leading our counterattack and facing Rory McIlroy in the most important match, while Paul Casey, Justin Rose, John Ram, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Polter will face the other Europeans in the top half of the standings.
"I chose these players in this order because I think that gives us the best chance of success", Björn said of his choice for singles.
Germany is once again delaying the launch of a new warship.
The German Navy's newest frigate was due to enter service in 2014 to replace the ageing Cold War-era battleships, but that won't happen until at least next year due to faulty systems and skyrocketing costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has been delayed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit, which quoted an army spokesman.
The vessel was due to join the Navy in 2014, but problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the obsolete Bremen-class frigates.
Understandably, they will have a powerful cannon, a suite of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, and some stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important characteristics include longer maintenance periods  the newest frigates must be able to be used for up to two years before returning to home ports.
But the continuing delays mean that the advanced warships  that are said to allow Germany to demonstrate power overseas  will be old by the time they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated F125 made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the vessel and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media have cited a number of major "software and hardware flaws" that make the warship unusable if sent on a combat mission.
The software flaws are particularly important as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels will be operated by a crew of around 120 sailors  only half the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, the ship was found to be significantly overloaded, which reduced its efficiency and limited the Navy's ability to add future superstructures.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is thought to be twice as heavy as the similar class of ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project  including crew training  also becomes an issue.
It is estimated to have reached a staggering €3.1 billion ($3.6 billion)  from the initial €2.2 billion.
The problems with the newest frigates are especially important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, admitted that the fleet was actually running out of ships capable of carrying out missions.
The official said that the problem has become more acute over time as old ships have been decommissioned but no new ones have been provided.
He complained that not a single Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigate could be inducted into the fleet.
The National Trust monitors the secret lives of bats
A new study conducted at a manor house in the Scottish Highlands aims to determine how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hopes are that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common bats as well as the brown arrow-tailed waterbeds at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations on the property to track the bat's activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the bats' call sounds, as well as which species are emitting them.
A habitat map and report will then be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of grasslands, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and Britain as a whole have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to habitat loss.
The risk to the population may be from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Actually, bats are not blind.
However, because of their night-hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation techniques to detect insects and obstacles along their flight path.
NTS, which oversees the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance, and 76,000 acres of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, shelter inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation even established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at Threave Manor in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, says it's the perfect territory for them.
"Here in Threave, we have a great bathing ground", he said.
We have old buildings, very old trees and a complete suitable habitat.
But there's still a lot about bats that we don't know, so the work we're doing here and at other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.
He stresses that it is important to check for bats before carrying out property maintenance activities, as the unintentional destruction of a shelter can kill up to 400 females and young bats, as well as wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their habitat.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, "I still have a lot to learn about our bats and a lot of our animal species, because we just don't know what's happening to their populations".
Ronaldo denies rape allegations and his lawyers are suing a German magazine.
Cristiano Ronaldo called the rape allegations against him "fake news", saying people "want to become famous" using his name.
His lawyers will sue the German news magazine Der Spiegel, which published these allegations.
The Portugal and Juventus forward was accused of raping American Catherine Majorga in a Las Vegas hotel room in 2009.
He allegedly then paid her $375,000 to keep the incident quiet, Der Spiegel reported on Friday.
In an Instagram video addressed to his 142 million followers, hours after the allegations were published, the 33-year-old Ronaldo denounced the post as "fake news".
No, no, no, no, no, no. I'm not going to do this.
"What was said about me today is fake news", said the five-time Ballon d'Or winner on camera.
They want to be famous by using my name.
It's not a bad thing.
They want to build up popularity behind my back, but that's part of the job.
I'm a happy man and everything's fine", smiled the footballer.
Ronaldo's lawyers are preparing to sue Der Spiegel for allegations they call "unacceptable publication of suspicious privacy", according to Reuters.
Lawyer Christian Schertz said the footballer will seek compensation for "moral damage" in an amount commensurate with the severity of the violation, which is probably one of the most serious violations of privacy in recent years.
The incident in question allegedly occurred in June 2009 in an apartment at the Palms Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas.
After meeting at a nightclub, Ronaldo and Majorga went to the football player's room, where he allegedly raped her anal, according to documents filed in Clark County District Court in Nevada.
Majorga claims that after the accident, Ronaldo fell on his knees and told her he was a "99% good guy", but in this case he just gave in to the "1%".
According to the documents, Ronaldo confirmed that they had sex, but it happened with her consent.
Majorga also claims that she went to the police and had her injuries photographed in hospital, but later agreed to an out-of-court settlement because she felt "scared of revenge" and was worried about "being publicly humiliated".
The 34-year-old woman says she wants to cancel the agreement as she continues to live with the trauma of the incident in question.
At the time of the incident, Ronaldo was on the verge of joining Real Madrid from Manchester United, and this summer he moved to Italian giants Juventus for a fee of €100 million.
Brexit: Britain will forever regret losing its car manufacturers
Britain will forever regret losing its status as the world's leading car manufacturer after Brexit, said Commerce Secretary Greg Clark.
He added that it was 'worrying' that Toyota UK told the BBC that if the UK left the EU without a deal, they would temporarily stop production at their plant in Burnton, near Derby.
"We need a deal", he said.
The Japanese carmaker said the impact of a delay at the border in a no-deal Brexit could lead to job losses.
The Burnton plant  where the Auris and Avensis  are produced last year produced almost 150 000 cars, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
"My view is that if the UK leaves the EU at the end of March, production at our plant will stop", said Marvin Cook, Toyota's head of Burnton.
Other UK carmakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have expressed concerns about leaving the EU without a deal and how cross-border trade would work.
BMW, for example, say they're going to close their Mini factory in Oxford for a month after Brexit.
The main concerns of car manufacturers are related to the risks to the supply chain in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line operates on the 'on time' principle, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers in both the UK and EU for custom cars.
If Britain leaves the EU without a deal on March 29, there could be problems at the border, which industry says could lead to delays and parts shortages.
It would be impossible for Toyota to wait more than a day to replenish its inventory at the Darbyshire plant, the company said, and so production would stop.
Mr Clarke said Theresa May's "chessboard" plan for the future relationship with the EU was "precisely calibrated to avoid these border checks".
"We need to have a deal.We want to make the best deal that will allow us, as I say, not only to enjoy the current success but to be able to seize this opportunity", he told BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
Following the claims made not only by Toyota but also by other manufacturers, we are absolutely convinced that we must be able to continue to ensure successful supply chains.
Toyota cannot say how long the shutdown will last, but in the longer term, they warn that the additional costs will reduce the factory's competitiveness and ultimately lead to job losses.
Peter Tsvalaris, who has worked at Burnton for 24 years and is the founder of the Unite union at the plant, said its members are increasingly worried: "From my experience, if these jobs go, they will never come back.
A government spokesman said: 'We have set out a clear and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU.'
Trump-Rosenstein meeting may be postponed again, White House says
The crucial meeting between Donald Trump and Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein may be postponed for another week as Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh continues his fight, the White House said Sunday.
Rosenstein is overseeing the work of special counsel Robert Mueller, who is investigating Russian election interference, ties between Trump aides and Russia, and potential obstruction of justice by the president.
Whether or not Trump will fire the deputy attorney general and thereby jeopardize Mueller's independence has been fueling rumours about Washington for months.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein was discussing the possibility of wearing a microphone to record conversations with Trump, as well as the possibility of removing the president through the 25th Amendment.
Rosenstein denies that claim.
But last Monday, he went to the White House after reports that he was resigning.
Instead, while Trump was at the United Nations in New York, a meeting with him was announced for Thursday.
Trump said he "would have preferred not to fire Rosenstein", but then the meeting was postponed to avoid a conflict with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing, which was witnessed by both Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him of sexual harassment, Dr. Christine Blaze Ford.
On Friday, Trump ordered a week-long FBI investigation into the complaints against Kavanaugh, further delaying the full Senate vote.
Trump's spokeswoman, Sarah Sanders, appeared on Fox News on Sunday.
When asked about the Rosenstein meeting, she said, "There's no date set for that yet, it could be this week, but seeing all the other things that are happening in the Supreme Court, I think it could be pushed back to next week.
But we'll see, and I always try to keep the press informed.
Some reporters would dispute this claim: Sanders did not hold a press conference from the White House on September 10th.
The host of the show, Chris Wallace, asked why.
Sanders responded that the rare press conferences were not because of a dislike of "demonstrative behavior" by television journalists, although he did say: "I can't say I disagree with the fact that they have demonstrative behavior".
Then she hinted that direct contact between Trump and the press would increase.
"The president has more Q&A sessions than any president before him", she said, adding, without citing evidence: "We've checked those statistics".
There will still be press conferences, Sanders continued, but if the press has a chance to ask questions directly to the president of the United States, that's far better than talking to me.
We try to do this often, and you've seen us practice it quite often in recent weeks, and it will replace press conferences once you have the opportunity to speak with the President of the United States.
Trump regularly answers questions when he leaves the White House or attends open meetings or press conferences with visiting dignitaries.
Independent press conferences are a rarity.
This week in New York, the president may have shown why, with his eccentric and at times bizarre behavior before a gathering of reporters.
The Minister for Health addresses EU workers at the Scottish National Health Service on Brexit fears
The Minister for Health has written to EU staff working at the Scottish National Health Service to express the country's gratitude and wishes for them to remain in their posts after Brexit.
Gene Freeman, a member of the Scottish Parliament, sent a letter to less than six months before Britain leaves the EU.
The Scottish Government has already committed to the costs of the established procedures for the status of EU citizens working in the decentralised public services.
In her letter, Ms Freeman wrote: "The UK-EU negotiations on leaving continued over the summer, with decisions expected this autumn.
But the UK government is also making progress in preparing for a possible no-deal scenario.
I'm sure this is a very uncertain time for all of you.
So I want to remind you how much I appreciate the contribution of every employee, no matter their nationality.
Colleagues from across the EU and beyond bring in valuable experience and skills that strengthen and improve the work of health services, benefiting patients and the communities we serve.
Scotland is your home without question and we would very much like you to stay here.
Christian Abercrombie underwent emergency surgery after suffering a head injury.
Tennessee State Tigers linebacker Christian Abercrombie underwent emergency surgery after sustaining a head injury during Saturday's game when his team lost to the Vanderbilt Commodores 31-27, Tennessee's Mike Organ reported.
Tennessee State head coach Rod Reed told reporters that the injury occurred just before halftime.
"He went to the sideline and somehow just passed out there", Reid said.
Coaches and paramedics administered oxygen to Abercrombie at the sideline before he was put on a stretcher and taken to the locker room for further examination.
A Tennessee State official confirmed to Chris Harris of WSMV in Nashville, Tennessee that Abercrombie has been released from surgery at Vanderbilt Medical Center.
Harris added that "there are still no details on the type/severity of the injury" and that Tennessee State is trying to determine when the injury occurred.
Abercrombie, a sophomore on a college scholarship, is in his first season at Tennessee State since transferring from Illinois.
On Saturday, he made a total of five blocks before leaving the game, making 18 blocks for him this season.
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp duty when buying property in the UK
Under new Conservative plans, foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp duty on UK property purchases, with the extra money to help the homeless.
This move would neutralize the success of Corbyn's efforts to attract young voters.
The stamp duty increase will affect those who do not pay taxes in the UK.
The Treasury expects an increase of over 120 million British pounds a year to help the homeless.
Theresa May will announce today that foreign buyers will pay a higher stamp duty on property purchases in the UK, with the extra proceeds going to help homeless people.
This move will be seen as an attempt to offset the success of Jeremy Corbyn's efforts to attract young voters by promising more affordable housing and targeting high-income people.
The increase in the stamp duty will affect individuals and businesses who do not pay taxes in the UK, and the additional revenue will support the government's efforts to limit the number of people sleeping on the streets.
The supplement  which is in addition to the current stamp duty, including the higher rates introduced two years ago for second homes and property purchased for the purpose of surrender  may amount to up to three per cent.
The Treasury expects revenues to increase by up to 120 million British pounds a year.
About 13 per cent of newly built buildings in London are bought by people with non-UK citizenship, which drives up prices and makes it harder for first-time buyers to enter the property market.
Many of the wealthy areas  especially in the capital  have become ghost towns due to the large number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a reduction in the stamp duty to help more young people own their first home.
He accused the big building firms of keeping property prices high by plundering land but not using it, and asked Mrs May to abandon affordable housing quotas to fix Britain's housing scandal.
Mr. Corbyn has announced an attractive series of proposals for housing reform, including rent control and an end to "no-fault" evictions.
He also wants to give the councils more power to build new homes.
Mrs May said: "Last year I said I would like to devote my time as Prime Minister to restoring the British dream of a better life for each new generation.
And that means fixing our broken housing market.
Britain will always have its doors open to those who wish to live, work and build their lives here.
But it is not right for non-UK residents and foreign companies to buy homes as easily as hardworking UK residents.
For too many people, the dream of owning a home has gone too far in time, and the insult of sleeping on the street remains too realistic.
Jack Ross: "My ultimate goal is to lead the Scotland team".
Sunderland manager Jack Ross has said that his "greatest career ambition" is to be the head coach of the Scottish national team.
The 42-year-old Scot has taken on the challenge of reviving the north-east English club, who are currently third in the Premier League, three points off the top spot.
He moved to the Stadium of Light this summer after guiding St Mirren back to the Scottish Premier League last season.
I wanted to play for my country as a player.
I recorded one game for the B team and that was it", Ross told BBC Sportsound in Scotland.
But I grew up watching Scotland's Hampden games, which I watched as a kid with my father, so the national team has always been something I've been attracted to.
However, this opportunity would only open up if I was successful at club level.
Ross' predecessors as Sunderland managers included names such as Dick Advocate, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paolo DiCanio.
The former manager of Alloa Athletic said he had no qualms about inheriting such established names at such a famous club, having previously turned down offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
For me, success right now will be measured by answering the question, "Can I get this club back to the Premier League?"
Because in terms of structure, base and conditions, he's definitely at the level of the Major League", he said.
It won't be easy to get back to the top level of football, but I'll only consider myself a success here if I can get the team back there.
Ross has only been manager for three years, after spending time as assistant manager at Dumbarton and 15 months on the coaching staff at Hearts.
He then helped Alloa avoid relegation to the Third Division and turned St Mirren from a relegated side into a Championship winner the following season.
Ross says he now feels more comfortable than during his playing career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"I was really at a crossroads", he recalls the time he took Aloha.
I really believed that being a manager was the best thing for me, including before I was an active player.
It sounds strange, because I was doing well, making good money, and having some significant success.
But being a player is hard sometimes.
There's a lot of stuff you have to deal with every week.
I'm still facing the same levels of stress and tension at work, but I just feel like being a manager is the right direction for me.
I've always wanted to be a manager, and now that I'm really doing it, I've never felt more comfortable in my own skin in my entire conscious life.
