The ideal time for a beer is 5:30pm on a Saturday, a study reveals.
The summer heat has boosted the revenues of Britain's struggling pubs, but it has added to the strain on restaurant chains.
Pub and bar groups reported a 2.7 percent increase in sales in July, but restaurant revenues fell 4.8 percent, statistics show.
Peter Martin of business consultancy CGA, which compiled the statistics, said: "Due to the prolonged sunny weather and longer than expected for England's World Cup appearance, July follows a similar pattern to June when pubs saw growth of 2.8 percent but restaurants took an even bigger hit.
The 1.8 percent drop in the restaurant business in June only deepened in July.
Pubs and liquor bars, they had the best performance in their growth, compared to the downward movement of restaurants.
The food bars were also hit by the sunny weather, but not as badly as the restaurant owners.
Looks like people just wanted to go out and have a drink.
In pubs and bars, beverage sales jumped 6.6 percent in the month, while food sales fell 3 percent.
Paul Newman, of leisure and entertainment analysts RSM, said: These results continue the trend we saw at the end of April.
The timing and impact of major social or sporting events remain the biggest factors when it comes to sales in the out-of-home services sector.
It is no surprise that restaurant groups continue to suffer, although a decline in sales of 4.8 percent year on year can be particularly painful in addition to the ongoing costs.
The long hot summer could not have come at a worse time for restaurant managers and only time will tell if the more moderate temperatures we experienced in August will bring the much-desired break.
The overall sales growth in pubs and restaurants, including newly opened ones, was 2.7 percent in July, reflecting the slowdown in brand deployment.
Coffer Peach Tracker, the UK pub, bar and restaurant sales analyst, collects and analyses performance data from 47 operating groups with a combined turnover of over GBP 9 billion and is a recognised industry benchmark.
One in five children has a secret social networking account that they hide from their parents
One in five children  some as young as 11  has a secret social networking account that they hide from their parents and teachers, a study reveals
A survey of 20,000 high school students shows a rise in fake Insta pages
News reports have raised fears of sexual content being posted
Twenty percent of the students said they had a "basic" profile that they showed their parents.
One in five children  some one in 11  create a social networking account that they keep secret from adults.
A survey of 20,000 high school students shows a rise in fake Instagram accounts  linking to the photo-sharing site Instagram.
The news has raised fears of sexual content being posted.
Twenty percent of the students said they had a clean "main" profile to show their parents, but they also had secret profiles.
A mother who stumbled upon her 13-year-old daughter's secret website found a teenage child who encouraged others to rape her.
A survey by Digital Awareness UK and the Headmasters' Conference (HMC) of independent schools found that 40 per cent of 11 to 18-year-olds have two accounts, with half admitting to keeping their accounts secret.
HMC's CEO Mike Buchanan said: "It's alarming that so many teenagers are tempted to create online spaces where parents and teachers can't find them".
