Earthquakes and Tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people have been killed by a powerful earthquake and tsunami that hit the Indonesian city of Palo on Friday, authorities said, with the death toll expected to rise.
Due to the disruption of communications, aid agencies are unable to receive information from the Donggala Regency, an area north of Palo, which is closer to the epicenter of the 7.5-magnitude quake.
In Palo, more than 16,000 people were evacuated after the disaster.
Here are some basic facts about Palu and Dongala, located on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi Province, located at the end of a narrow beach strip on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with a population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami hit.
Dongala is a regency that stretches for more than 300 km (180 mi) along the coastline of Sulawesi Island.
The regency, which is an administrative region smaller than a province, has an approximate population of 299 200 in 2017.
Fishing and farming are the mainstays of the economy of Central Sulawesi Province, especially in the coastal region of Dongola.
Nickel mining is also important for the province but is mainly concentrated in Morawai, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by several tsunamis in the past 100 years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Recovery Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of buildings in Dongala.
A tsunami hit western Dongala in 1996 when nine people died.
Indonesia is located in the seismically active Pacific Ring of Fire and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunami waves in recent years:
2004: A powerful earthquake on December 26 off the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in North Sumatra triggers a tsunami wave that hits 14 countries and kills 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coastline, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake hit Indonesia's most populous island, Java, triggering a tsunami that struck the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake strikes near the city of Padang, capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake shook one of the Mentawai Islands and triggered a 10-meter-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake hits the Pidi Jaya Regency in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people remember the devastation of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time no tsunami was triggered, but over 100 people were killed by collapsed buildings.
2018: Strong earthquakes hit the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia, killing more than 500 people, mostly in the northern part of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and temporarily left thousands of tourists stranded.
