Federal prosecutors are seeking the rare death penalty for a suspect in a terrorist attack in New York City.
Federal prosecutors in New York are seeking the death penalty for Saifullo Saipov, the suspect in the New York City terrorist attack that killed eight people -- a rare sentence that has not been carried out in the state for a federal crime since 1953.
It's alleged that Saipov, 30, used a truck rented from Home Depot to carry out the October bombing at a bike lane near the West Side Highway in lower Manhattan, trampling pedestrians and cyclists on its way.
To justify the death penalty, prosecutors will have to prove that Saipov intentionally killed eight victims and intentionally inflicted grievous bodily harm, according to the intent notice in connection with the death penalty request filed in the Southern District of New York.
According to the court document, both charges could result in a death sentence.
Weeks after the bombing, an expanded federal grand jury indicted Saipov on 22 counts, including eight counts of murder related to racketeering, commonly used by federal prosecutors in organized crime cases, as well as one count of assault and vehicular manslaughter.
The attack required "serious planning and deliberation", prosecutors said, describing Saipov's manner of execution as "horrific, brutal and perverse".
"Sayfullo Habibulayevich Saipov has caused injury, damage and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleaves, Ann-Lori Decad, Darren Drake, Ariel Earley, Ernan Feluci and Alejandro Damian Panuko", the notice said.
Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
It's been a decade since the Southern District of New York last sought the death penalty.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was charged with the murder of two drug dealers, but was subsequently sentenced to life in prison in September 2009.
The last time a federal death sentence was carried out in New York was in 1953 for Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a married couple who were executed after being convicted of conspiracy and spying for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
Both Rosenbergs were executed in the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
Saipov, a native Uzbek, showed no remorse in the days and months following the attack, according to court documents.
He told investigators he felt good about what he did, police say.
Saipov told authorities he was inspired to carry out the attack after watching ISIS videos on his phone, the indictment says.
He also requested that the ISIS flag be placed in his hospital room, police said.
He pleads not guilty to the charge of 22 counts.
David Patton, one of the federal public defenders representing Saipov, noted that they were "obviously disappointed" by the prosecutor's decision.
"We believe that the decision to seek the death penalty instead of accepting a guilty verdict and life in prison without the possibility of parole will only prolong the traumatic effect of these events on all concerned", Patton said.
Saipov's defense team has previously asked the prosecution not to seek the death penalty.
